Achalasia","Cerebrovascular accident","Gastric carcinoma","Oesophageal web","Scleroderma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOropharyngeal dysphagia involves problems with the initiation of swallowing. \u003Cstrong\u003ECerebrovascular accident\u003C/strong\u003E is a common cause, affecting the neurological control of swallowing. Some 40 - 60 % of patients experience dysphagia following acute ischaemic stroke and about 50% will still be affected six months later. Other potential neurological causes include Parkinson disease and motor neuron disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options represent causes of oesophageal dysphagia and are less common:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAchalasia\u003C/strong\u003E is a motility disorder affecting the lower oesophageal sphincter. The incidence in Australia is less than 3 per 100,000 persons.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal web\u003C/strong\u003E is a mechanical obstruction in the upper oesophagus and its incidence in Australia is less than 5 per 100,000 persons.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScleroderma\u003C/strong\u003E affects oesophageal muscle function through fibrosis. The incidence in Australia is about 17 per 100,000 persons. Only a small proportion of these patients have dysphagia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastric carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E may cause mechanical obstruction at the gastro-oesophageal junction, but most of these tumours are below the cardia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dysphagia can be classified into oropharyngeal (transfer) and oesophageal (transport) causes","Oropharyngeal dysphagia commonly presents with difficulty initiating swallowing and immediate coughing or choking","Common oropharyngeal causes include neurological conditions, muscular disorders, and structural abnormalities"],"references":["Panebianco M, Marchese-Ragona R, Masiero S, Restivo DA. Dysphagia in neurological diseases: a literature review. Neurol Sci. 2020 Nov;41(11):3067-3073. doi: 10.1007/s10072-020-04495-2. Epub 2020 Jun 7. PMID: 32506360; PMCID: PMC7567719","Wilkinson JM, Codipilly DC, Wilfahrt RP. Dysphagia: Evaluation and Collaborative Management. Am Fam Physician. 2021 Jan 15;103(2):97-106. PMID: 33448766","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50240"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15116"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50240"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-24T17:55:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-24T17:56:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7804"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64806"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups",